## The definition

- Class: [FrameworkController](#api~FrameworkController)

### PROPERTY: exports.id;

`optional` Can contain only controller name (it's an identificator name). A __default value__ for this property is controller filename without extension.

```javascript
exports.id = 'Controller name';
```

### METHOD: exports.install;

`optional` `important` This is the initialization function of the controller. This function is executed when framework loads controllers and this function is a scope for define routes. A route can be defined inline, outside of install function.

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
    framework.route('/');
    framework.route('/api/{type}/', json_api, ['put', 'json']);
};
```

### METHOD: exports.uninstall;

`optional` This function is executed when framework uninstalls the controller.

```javascript
exports.uninstall = function() {
    console.log('This controller is uninstalled.');
};
```

### METHOD: exports.usage;

`optional` This function must return exploitation of controller. [Example: Usage](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-usage).

```javascript
exports.usage = function() {
    return { requests: counter };
};
```

### Full example of controller

Filename: `controllers/default.js`

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
    framework.route('/', view_index);
    framework.route('/contact/', view_contact);
    framework.route('/hello/', plain_hello);
    framework.route('/api/codelist/', json_codelist, ['xhr', 'get']);
};

function view_index() {
    this.view('index');
}

function view_contact() {
    this.layout('layouts/subpage');
    this.view('contact', { email: '@' });
}

function plain_hello() {
    this.plain('Hello world!');
}

function json_codelist() {
    this.mail('info@company.com', 'Codelist notifications', 'mails/codelist');
    this.json([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]);
}

// or inline route
framework.route('/services/', function() {
    this.view('services');
});
```

## Routing

- Method: [framework.route()](#api~Framework~framework.route)
- Method: [framework.websocket()](#api~Framework~framework.websocket)
- Method: [framework.file()](#api~Framework~framework.file)
- List: [route flags](#api~HttpRouteOptionsFlags)

### System routing

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
    framework.route('#400', custom); // Bad Request
    framework.route('#401', custom); // Unauthorized
    framework.route('#403', custom); // Forbidden
    framework.route('#404', custom); // Not Found
    framework.route('#408', custom); // Request Timeout
    framework.route('#431', custom); // Request Header Fields Too Large
    framework.route('#500', custom); // Internal Server Error
    framework.route('#501', custom); // Not Implemented
}

function custom() {
    this.view('http-error-view');
}
```

Definitions can rewrite existing functionality or add new. The definition can define the framework behavior and it doesn't have any other logic. __In short__: the definition is a coded configuration file.

```plain
Initialization: Modules --> Packages --> Models --> Definitions --> Controllers
```

__More informations__

- The definitions is plain JavaScript file with `.js` extension.
- All definitions are stored in `your-app/definitions/` directory.
- Each definitions executed automatically and one time.
- You can create unlimited count of definitions
- The definition can be injected from URL address, [example](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-install-definition).

---

## Examples

Most [examples](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/) contain definitions.

- [Example: Install definition from URL](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-install-definition)
- [Example: Definition with MongoDB driver](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/mongodb)

---

## The definition

The definition file contains only code to run, nothing more.

### Full example of definition

E.g. create: `definitions/database.js`

```javascript
var DB = null;

require('mongodb').MongoClient.connect('connection-string-to-database', function(err, db) {
    if (err)
        throw err;
    DB = db;
});

// Rewrite built-in functionality
framework.database = function(collection) {
    if (collection)
        return DB.collection(collection);
    return DB;
};
```

Controllers are responsible for responding to requests from a web browser, mobile application or any other system capable of communicating with a server. Each route is mapped to some action and the action responds to requests. The controller with modules are the main features of the framework logic.

```plain
Initialization: Modules --> Packages --> Models --> Definitions --> Controllers
```

__More informations__

- The module is plain JavaScript file with `.js` extension.
- The framework automatically loads modules into the memory.
- All modules are stored in `your-app/modules/` directory.
- `exports.install` is executed automatically and one time.
- Views are loaded according to the controller name from `your-app/views/`.
- You can create unlimited count of modules.
- Module can be injected from URL address, [example](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-install-module).
- The module can communicate with other modules or controllers.
- [Download modules](https://github.com/totaljs/modules)

---

## Examples

- [Example: Modules](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-modules)

---

## The definition

### PROPERTY: exports.id;

`optional` Can contain only module name (it's an identificator name). A __default value__ for this property is module filename without extension.

```javascript
exports.id = 'Module name';
```

### PROPERTY: exports.dependencies;

`optional` Can contain only array of module names. Framework waits for all dependencies and then installs pending modules. The installation is meant execution: `exports.install`.

```javascript
exports.dependencies = ['moduleA', 'moduleC'];
```

### METHOD: exports.install;

`optional` `important` This is the initialization function of the module. This function is executed when framework loads modules. __Modules support routing.__

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
    console.log('Hello from module.');
    framework.route('/module/');
};
```

### METHOD: exports.uninstall;

`optional` This function is executed when framework uninstalls the module.

```javascript
exports.uninstall = function() {
    console.log('This module is uninstalled.');
};
```

### METHOD: exports.usage;

`optional` This function must return exploitation of module. [Example: Usage](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-usage).

```javascript
exports.usage = function() {
    return { requests: counter };
};
```

### Full example of module

Filename: `modules/counter.js`

```javascript
exports.id = 'counter';
exports.version = '1.01';

var counter = 0;

exports.install = function() {
    framework.on('request', increment);
    framework.route('/stats/', json_stats);
};

exports.uninstall = function() {
    framework.removeListener('request', increment);
};

exports.usage = function() {
    return { requests: counter };
}

function json_stats() {
    // The same behavior like in controller
    this.json({ requests: counter });
}

function increment() {
    counter++;
}
```

Models are good for databases schema.

```plain
Initialization: Modules --> Packages --> Models --> Definitions --> Controllers
```

__More informations__

- The model is plain JavaScript file with `.js` extension.
- The framework automatically loads models into the memory.
- All modules are stored in `your-app/models/` directory.
- `exports.install` is executed automatically and one time.
- You can create unlimited count of models.
- Model can be injected from URL address, [example](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-install-model).

---

## Examples

- [Example: Models](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/models)

---

## The definition

### PROPERTY: exports.id;

`optional` Can contain only model name (it's an identificator name). A __default value__ for this property is model filename without extension.

```javascript
exports.id = 'Model name';
```

### METHOD: exports.install;

`optional` `important` This is the initialization function of the module. This function is executed when framework loads models.

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
    console.log('Hello from model.');
};
```

### METHOD: exports.uninstall;

`optional` This function is executed when framework uninstalls the model.

```javascript
exports.uninstall = function() {
    console.log('This model is uninstalled.');
};
```

### METHOD: exports.usage;

`optional` This function must return exploitation of module. [Example: Usage](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-usage).

```javascript
exports.usage = function() {
    return { requests: counter };
};
```

### Full example of model

Filename: `models/user.js`

```javascript
exports.id = 'user';
exports.version = '1.01';

exports.create = function(user) {
    // NoSQL embedded database
    DATABASE('users').insert(user);
};

exports.load = function(id, callback) {
    // NoSQL embedded database
    DATABASE('users').one(function(doc) {
        return doc.id === id;
    }, callback);
}
```

Get the model in e.g. controller action:

```javascript
function json_create_user() {
    var user = { id: Utils.GUID(5), alias: 'Peter Sirka' };

    // global alias:
    MODEL('user').create(user);

    // or
    framework.model('user').create(user);

    this.json(user);
}
```

Total.js has a simple authorization mechanism. It's built on one delegate function `framework.onAuthorization()`. The authorization is asynchronous.

- You can create your own authorization mechanism (total.js gives open options).
- The authorization delegate is async.
- You can authorize user by the cookies / headers or request data.
- You can set user roles.
- Authorization delegate adds `authorize` and `unauthorize` flag by the state.
- Is executed each request.
- __Delegate does not handle static files.__
- [Example: authorization](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/authorization)
- [Download module: Auth](https://github.com/totaljs/modules/tree/master/auth)

---

![Authorization](resources/authorization.png)

---

## Simple example

Create e.g. definition:

```javascript
framework.onAuthorization = function(req, res, flags, next) {

    // EXAMPLE:
    var userId = req.cookie('user').parseInt();

    if (userId === 0) {
        // unauthorized user
        next(false);
        return;
    }

    var self = this;

    self.database('users').one(function(doc) { return doc.id === userId; }, function(user) {

        if (user === null) {
            // unauthorized user
            next(false);
            return;
        }

        // user is authorized
        next(true, user);

        // or assign the user object to request.user:
        /*
            req.user = user;
            next(true);
        */
    });
}
```

Usage in controllers:

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
    framework.route('/user/', view_logged, ['authorize']);
    framework.route('/user/', view_unlogged, ['unauthorize']);
}

function view_logged() {
    this.view('logged');
}

function view_unlogged() {
    this.view('unlogged');
}
```

The framework has a simple validation logic. The result from validation is [Builders.ErrorBuilder](#api~Builders.ErrorBuilder) and it contains all informations about errors. The framework knows two types of validation:

1. objects validation
2. schemas validation (recommended)

---

## Objects validation

- [Documentation: framework.onValidation()](#api~Framework~framework.onValidation)
- [Documentation: controller.validate()](#api~FrameworkController~controller.validate)
- [Documentation: Utils.validate()](#api~FrameworkUtils~utils.validate)
- [Example: Validation](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/validation)
- [Example: Custom validation](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/validation-custom)

Objects validation uses `framework.onValidation()` delegate for checking values by property name. Validation is linked with resources.

### Example

Create e.g. definition:

```javascript
framework.onValidation = function(name, value, path, schema, model) {
    switch (name) {
        case 'firstname':
        case 'lastname':
            return value.length > 0 ? 'Name is too short.' : true;
        case 'terms':
            return value.toString().parseBool();
        case 'age':
            var age = value.toString().parseInt();
            return age > 10 && age < 90;
        case 'email':
            return value.isEmail();
    }
}
```

Some action in some controller:

```javascript
function some_action_in_controller() {
    var self = this;
    var model = self.body; // POSTed data

    // Validate only: firstname, lastname
    // ErrorBuilder is linked with resources
    var error = self.validate(model, ['firstname', 'lastname'], 'error-');

    if (error.hasError()) {
        // Response: [{ "name": "firstname", "error": "First name is not valid.", path: "" }]
        // You can create a transformation for output of ErrorBuilder.
        self.json(error);
        return;
    }

    // insert the model into the DB
    self.database('users').insert(model);

    // response success
    self.json({ success: true });
}
```

Resource `default.resource`:

```html
error-firstname        : First name is not valid.
error-lastname         : Last name is not valid.
```

## Schemas validation

- [Documentation: Builders.SchemaBuilder](#api~Builders.SchemaBuilder)
- [Example: Schema validation](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-schema-validation)

### Example

Create e.g. definition:

```javascript
var schema = SCHEMA('my-group');
var User = schema.add('User');

User.define('alias', 'string(50)', true); // Framework trims long strings according to schema
User.define('age', Number);
User.define('email', String, true);
User.define('datecreated', Date);

// Set validation
User.setValidation(function(name, value, path, schema, model) {
    switch (name) {
        case 'alias':
            return value.length > 0;
        case 'age':
            return value > 15 && value < 80;
        case 'email':
            return value.isEmail();
    }
});

// User.setDefault(...)
// User.setSave(...)
// User.setGet(...)
// User.setQuery(...)
// User.setRemove(...)
```

Some action in some controller:

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
    framework.route('/add/', json_custom_schema, ['post']);
    framework.route('/add/schema/', json_schema, ['*my-group/User', 'post']);
}

function json_custom_schema() {
    var self = this;
    var model = self.body; // POSTed data

    SCHEMA('my-group', 'User').make(model, function(error, entity) {

        // Error === ErrorBuilder
        // Error can be null
        if (error) {
            self.json(error);
            return;
        }

        self.json(entity);
    });
}

// Framework automatically converts a request data according to schema and automatically handles error
function json_schema() {
    var self = this;
    var entity = self.body; // A prepared entity

    // schema.setSave() must be defined
    entity.$save(function(error, result) {
        // schema.addWorkflow() must be defined
        entity.$workflow('email', function() {
            self.json({ success: true });
        });
    });
}
```

## Note: ErrorBuilder transformation

As default are errors in `ErrorBuilder` serialized to JSON like Object Array. You can rewrite this transformations via [ErrorBuilder.addTransform()](#api~Builders.ErrorBuilder~ErrorBuilder.addTransform) and [ErrorBuilder.setTransform()](api~Builders.ErrorBuilder~ErrorBuilder.setDefaultTransform).

```json
[{ "name":"Property name", "error":"Error message", "path":"Path in current object"}]
```

### How to check errors on client-side?

```javascript
$.ajax('/add/', { type: 'POST', data: JSON.stringify({ age: 100 }), success: function(response) {

    if (typeof(response) === 'string')
        response = JSON.parse(response);

    // Check erros
    if (response instanceof Array) {
        showErrors(response);
        return;
    }

});
```
